Encanto - Isabela’s Ambition - Exploring the caret package

Adapted from a very useful tutorial on the caret package. https://www.machinelearningplus.com/machine-learning/caret-package/ by Selva Prabhakaran

Loading packages

library(caret) #hyperparameter tuning
library(skimr) #generate descriptive stats
library(RANN)  # required for knnInpute
library(caretEnsemble) #for ensembling predictions

Load dataset

data <- read.csv("Isabela.csv")
head(data)

Explanation (18 variables)
- Ambition Response/outcome variable. Isabela’s ambition to either to become a florist or a housewife
- Practice_min Number of minutes practicing her gift of conjuring flowers or cooking skills
- Prac_loc_ID Practice location
- Score_flower Aesthetics score for flowers created
- Score_cooking Score for dishes cooked
- Flower_deduct Aesthetics score deducted by Abuela
- Cooking_deduct Cooking score deducted by Abuela
- Special_flower Is special flower conjured?
- Special_dish Is special dish cooked?
- Support_florist Is Isabela’s ambition to become a florist supported by other people apart from Abuela?
- Ave_flower Average aesthetics score for flowers created
- Ave_cooking Average score for dishes cooked
- Score_diff Score difference
- Prac_loc_7 Is practice location called ‘7’?
- Pct_flower Percentage of aesthetics score deducted
- Pct_cook Percentage of cooking score deducted
- Ave_diff Average score difference
- Prac_loc Practice location

Split into train and test datasets

# Create the training and test datasets
set.seed(100)

# Get row numbers for the training data
trainRowNumbers <- createDataPartition(data$Ambition, p=0.8, list=FALSE)

# Create the training  dataset
trainData <- data[trainRowNumbers,]

# Create the test dataset
testData <- data[-trainRowNumbers,]

# Store X and Y for later use.
x = trainData[, 2:18]
y = trainData$Ambition

Impute missing values

Impute missing values using k-Nearest Neighbours using the preProcess function.

# Create the knn imputation model on the training data
preProcess_missingdata_model <- preProcess(trainData, method='knnImpute')
preProcess_missingdata_model
## Created from 827 samples and 18 variables
## 
## Pre-processing:
##   - centered (16)
##   - ignored (2)
##   - 5 nearest neighbor imputation (16)
##   - scaled (16)
# Use the imputation model to predict the values of missing data points
trainData <- predict(preProcess_missingdata_model, newdata = trainData)
anyNA(trainData)
## [1] FALSE

All missing values were imputed.

Create One-Hot Encoding (dummy variables)

Categorical variables need to be converted to numeric variables in order to run.

# Creating dummy variables is converting a categorical variable to as many binary variables as here are categories.
dummies_model <- dummyVars(Ambition ~ ., data=trainData)

# Create the dummy variables using predict. The Y variable (Ambition) will not be present in trainData_mat.
trainData_mat <- predict(dummies_model, newdata = trainData)

# # Convert to dataframe
trainData <- data.frame(trainData_mat)

# # See the structure of the new dataset

Visualise importance of variables

# y variable must be factor

trainData$Ambition <- as.factor(trainData$Ambition)

#pdf("boxplot.pdf", width=10, height=10)

featurePlot(x = trainData[, 1:18], 
            y = trainData$Ambition, 
            plot = "box",
            strip=strip.custom(par.strip.text=list(cex=.7)),
            scales = list(x = list(relation="free"), 
                          y = list(relation="free")))

#dev.off()

The black dot inside the boxe represent the mean.
The blue box shows the region where most data points lie.
Check out the Support_florist variable where the means and placement of the two boxes are different. Thus, this is an indication that the Support_florist variable is likely to be a significant predictor of Isabela’s ambition.
Likewise, Score_diff, Ave_flower and Score_cooking appear to have mean dots that are different for the two outcomes.

#pdf("density.pdf", width=10, height=10)

featurePlot(x = trainData[, 1:18], 
            y = trainData$Ambition, 
            plot = "density",
            strip=strip.custom(par.strip.text=list(cex=.7)),
            scales = list(x = list(relation="free"), 
                          y = list(relation="free")))

#dev.off()

Similarly, for the density plots, variables that are important are likely to have density curves that are significantly different for the two outcomes. Again, the Support_florist variable shows rather different density curves.

Feature selection with recursive feature elimination

Recursive feature elimination (RFE) is used for selecting important features that are predictive of the outcome.

set.seed(100)
options(warn=-1)

subsets <- c(1:5, 10, 15, 18)

ctrl <- rfeControl(functions = rfFuncs,
                   method = "repeatedcv",
                   repeats = 5,
                   verbose = FALSE)

lmProfile <- rfe(x=trainData[, 1:18], y=trainData$Ambition,
                 sizes = subsets,
                 rfeControl = ctrl)

Generate test dataset and run prediction

In order for the model to predict on the test dataset, we need to preprocess and transform the dataset just as we did on the train dataset.
All the information required for pre-processing is stored in preProcess_missingdata_model, dummies_model and preProcess_range_model.

# Step 1: Impute missing values 
testData2 <- predict(preProcess_missingdata_model, testData)  

# Step 2: Create one-hot encodings (dummy variables)
testData3 <- predict(dummies_model, testData2)

# Step 3: Transform the features to range between 0 and 1
testData4 <- predict(preProcess_range_model, testData3)

Evaluate performance of multiple algorithms

We can use the resamples function to evaluate multiple machine learning models. Let’s start by training some algorithms.

We can perform hyperparameter tuning using the train function in two ways:

Set the tuneLength
Define and set the tuneGrid

tuneLength = the number of unique values for tuning parameters. Caret will automatically determine the values each parameter should take.

tuneGrid = allows you to control what values should be considered for each parameter.

First, let’s set up the trainControl.

# Define the training control
fitControl <- trainControl(
    method = 'cv',                   # k-fold cross validation
    number = 5,                      # number of folds
    savePredictions = 'final',       # saves predictions for optimal tuning parameter
    classProbs = T,                  # should class probabilities be returned
    summaryFunction=twoClassSummary  # results summary function, use twoClassSummary if the response variable is binary class
)

Training MARS

# Step 1: Define the tuneGrid
marsGrid <-  expand.grid(nprune = c(2, 4, 6, 8, 10), 
                        degree = c(1, 2, 3))

# Step 2: Tune hyper parameters by setting tuneGrid
set.seed(100)
model_mars3 = train(Ambition ~ ., data=trainData, method='earth', metric='ROC', tuneGrid = marsGrid, trControl = fitControl)

# Compare model performances using resample()

Ensembling the predictions

We have predictions from multiple individual models and we can use the caretEnsemble package. All we need to do is to put the names of the algorithms and pass it to the caretList function instead of the train function.

# Stacking Algorithms - Run multiple algos in one call.
trainControl <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", 
                             number=10, 
                             repeats=3,
                             savePredictions=TRUE, 
                             classProbs=TRUE)

algorithmList <- c('rf', 'adaboost', 'earth', 'svmRadial')

set.seed(100)
models <- caretList(Ambition ~ ., data=trainData, trControl=trainControl, methodList=algorithmList) 
results <- resamples(models)
summary(results)

Combine predictions from multiple models into a final prediction

Let’s combine these predicted values from multiple models and create a new ensemble that predicts better using the caretStack function.

# Create the trainControl
set.seed(101)
stackControl <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", 
                             number=10, 
                             repeats=3,
                             savePredictions=TRUE, 
                             classProbs=TRUE)

# Ensemble the predictions of `models` to form a new combined prediction based on glm
stack.glm <- caretStack(models, method="glm", metric="Accuracy", trControl=stackControl)
print(stack.glm)
